<dateline>WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 18, 1843.</dateline> <lb/> <pb n="3" facs="#f0001"/> <div n="1"> <head><hi rendition="#k">Great Mass of Native Gold.</hi></head> <p>&#x2014;In the valley of Tachkou<lb/>Targanka, at the spot on which stood the workshops for wash-<lb/>ing the sand, there was discovered, on the 7th of November,<lb/>1842, under the very corner of the building, at three metres<lb/>(ten feet) depth, resting upon a stratum of diorite, a mon-<lb/>ster lump of gold, weighing two poods, seven Russian pounds,<lb/>and 92 zolotniks (79lb 1,625 dec.) This mass has an undu-<lb/>lated surface; it is somewhat porous, and free from all trace<lb/>of matrix or gangue. The largest lump of native platina<lb/>hitherto found in the platiniferous alluvia of Nijni-Taguilsk,<lb/>weighs 20 Russian pounds and 34 zolotniks (= 18,319lb.)&#x2014;<lb/><hi rendition="#i">From Humboldt&#x2019;s</hi> new work, entitled &#x201C;<hi rendition="#i">Asie Centrale.</hi>&#x201D; </p> </div> <lb/> </body><back></back>
